column70: Matching someone does not automatically mean that you will meet up. Imagine dating apps as a funnel. The first step is matching with someone, which might happen out of sheer coincidence (e.g. people swipe right on accident). Even if not, people might not want to write to each other and leave the matches untouched. Now the second step would be a mutual conversation, which might turn out sour if you fail to choose the right approach. The third step is the exchange of contact details (e.g. phone number, snapchat). At this step people might find their partner boring or simply fail to find a time to meet-up. Only the fourth step is an in-person meet-up. Remember, at any of these stages of the funnel people might lose interest in each other. I believe that the match : date ratio is above 1:10, so it is not unusual not to meet-up in person.
column75: Excited to see what you guys fabricated.
column79: I've met a diverse array of girls within different social strata. Some were more casual, adventurous type of girls while others were more "classy". Some were even enjoyably arrogant. Not knowing what might happen when meeting the girls was the most exciting bit for me. I've learned how to filter by asking the right questions so I'd generally not be disappointed with my date before meeting them. But what would be truly amazing is to meet the person you want to meet based on your preferences and choices.
